parameters:
"Damn it... damn it all... everyone, everyone is
dead..."\n<Male Ghost>

"Challenging such a monster... Master, and big
brother too... they've become cursed..."\n<Male Ghost>

(This person... he hasn't realized that he's
passed away...)\F[8]

"Damn it... I don't want to be eaten, don't want
to become cursed... I hate frogs"\n<Male Ghost>\AA[N]\F[8]
(It's no use... he's lost his mind.)\F[10]

(What's this? There's a scroll lying here. It
looks like it can still be read.)

In the seventh year of Tenpou, on the last day of
Kisaragi, the waves of famine grew fierce, and
many died of starvation. The grudge that absorbed
these resentments became ever more powerful, and
there was no longer any time to spare.

We gathered our elite to recruit a group for the
purpose of purification.

In the seventh year of Tenpou, in the third month
of Yayoi, we united beyond the barriers of our
sectarian doctrines to drive the curse into this
village. The villagers had already been consumed
by the curse, pitifully transformed into frogs.

We must slay the evil god that feeds on human
lamentations. With over eighty of us, each
gripping a vajra, I felt reassured by the presence
of my brother, hailed as a genius.

In the seventh year of Tenpou, on the sixth day of
Yayoi, we successfully lured the curse into our
barrier formation. Even though it took the form of
a child, we could not let our guard down, and
already about twenty had become sacrifices.

Grateful for the results our master staked his
life on, we gathered our fellow disciples to pray
and vowed to destroy the curse on his remains.

In the seventh year of Tenpou, in the month of
Uzuki, how many days have passed since we captured
the curse? No matter how much we recite sutras or
burn goma, there is no sign of it weakening.
Countless comrades have fallen to the miasma, and
all are reaching their physical limits.

In the seventh year of Tenpou, I've lost count of
the days. Another comrade has gone mad from the
curse. I've forgotten how many that makes now.

There's no one left, not my brother nor my peers.
My throat has been sore for so long. Is our power
even reaching the child's curse?

In Tenpou, I've come to know why I am still alive.
The curse... that god knew I was keeping records.

Everyone's dead except for me; they've all been
turned into frogs. The curse is laughing behind
me. I will leave behind the name of the curse at
last. Its name is Sakka Tsuki.

It's a god beyond human control, terrifying. I am
terrified. Oh Sakka Tsuki-sama, please don't turn
me into a frog.
"Sakka Tsuki... That's the name of that curse."\n<Yukine>\F[4]

"Yeah... I feel like I've heard that name before.
But I can't quite remember."\n<Saku>\F[4]\AA[FF]\FF[24]

"I see... Well, there's no use thinking about it
now. Let's move on ahead for now."\n<Yukine>\F[4]\AA[F]\FF[24]

We have found traces of that ancient deity, our
sect's archenemy, harboring centuries of grudges.
To stand against the deep-seated enmity that has
persisted from the past, we have honed our
techniques.

We've faced difficulties. The master of this house
is not cooperating. It seems he thinks of us as a
suspicious religious group because he lacks
spiritual sensitivity.
"What is this... Such an intense aura of a curse."\n<Yukine>\F[10]

(I want to do something about it, but I can't
break the source of the curse with my current
powers...)\F[10]

"This seems to be... the cause of the curse. It
was hidden in such a place."\n<Yukine>\F[4]

"Yeah. It doesn't seem like there's any strange
presence here."\n<Yukine>\F[1]
"Saku, it's dangerous, so stay back a little."\n<Yukine>\F[1]
